{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17629160","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17629160"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:04:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:04:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17259"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17259","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17259"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9949"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77912"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9949","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9949"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17259"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63390"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"10722"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23321"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23325"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77912"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EIn a genetics experiment, pea plants that are pure-breeding for tall height are crossed with pure-breeding short plants. All offspring in the first generation (F1) are tall. When these F1 plants are crossed with each other, the second generation (F2) produces tall and short plants in a 3:1 ratio.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pattern of inheritance demonstrated in these pea plants?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Equal expression of both alleles","Complete dominance of the tall allele","Codominance between height alleles","Incomplete dominance of height","Random expression of height alleles"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis inheritance pattern demonstrates \u003Cstrong\u003Ecomplete dominance of the tall allele\u003C/strong\u003E over the short allele. In the F1 generation, all offspring are tall because they inherit one dominant tall allele and one recessive short allele. The tall phenotype completely masks the short allele in heterozygous plants. The 3:1 ratio in the F2 generation is characteristic of complete dominance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEqual expression of both alleles\u003C/strong\u003E - This would result in both height alleles being expressed equally, producing an intermediate phenotype\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECodominance between height alleles\u003C/strong\u003E - This would result in both alleles being expressed simultaneously, producing a distinct third phenotype\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncomplete dominance of height\u003C/strong\u003E - This would result in F1 plants having an intermediate height between tall and short\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERandom expression of height alleles\u003C/strong\u003E - This would result in random height patterns rather than the consistent tall phenotype in F1 and 3:1 ratio in F2\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EComplete dominance, first described by Mendel in pea plants, results in only two possible phenotypes (tall or short) despite three possible genotypes (homozygous dominant, heterozygous, and homozygous recessive).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Dominant alleles mask the expression of recessive alleles in heterozygous individuals.","Complete dominance occurs when the heterozygous phenotype is identical to the homozygous dominant phenotype.","Alleles that show complete dominance produce only two possible phenotypes in a population, regardless of the three possible genotypes."],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Genetics E-Book: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2011"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63390"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17259"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63390"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T20:37:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T20:39:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9949"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77912"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4945","